07:32.844 --> 07:35.579
So... I thought she could use
a little help around the house.

07:35.614 --> 07:37.681
The real question is,
Rachel Berry...

07:37.716 --> 07:39.450
what are you doing here?

07:39.484 --> 07:41.518
What? I'm coaching
the glee club.

07:41.553 --> 07:43.754
Yeah, we're-we're cramming
for sectionals right now, so...

07:43.788 --> 07:45.456
Well, I heard you were
offered a new role

07:45.490 --> 07:47.658
in the Russell Simmons musical
opposite one of Broadway's

07:47.692 --> 07:49.627
hottest up-and-coming young
actors, but that the producers

07:49.661 --> 07:51.261
are still waiting
to hear back from you.

07:51.296 --> 07:52.696
Wait, how do you know that?

07:52.731 --> 07:54.298
Because I'm the hot
up-and-coming young actor

07:54.332 --> 07:56.500
that you're going
to play opposite of.

07:56.534 --> 07:57.968
You're playing Tino?

07:58.003 --> 07:59.770
The Iraqi War vet who was
discharged for covering

07:59.804 --> 08:01.804
the American embassy
with the graffiti that he used

08:01.806 --> 08:03.674
to make him a famous
Philly street artist,

08:03.708 --> 08:05.476
and when he comes home
crippled with PTSD,

08:05.510 --> 08:07.945
it's only his love of hip-hop
that can save his life?

08:07.979 --> 08:08.979
(laughs) Yeah.

08:09.014 --> 08:10.681
The producer spent a month

08:10.715 --> 08:12.850
trying the cast the role
of Segovia Shade

08:12.884 --> 08:14.485
until I finally reminded them

08:14.519 --> 08:16.487
they found their Segovia Shade.

08:16.521 --> 08:19.023
She auditioned for them.
Her name is Rachel Berry.

08:19.057 --> 08:21.692
Jessie, I really appreciate you
doing that for me,

08:21.726 --> 08:24.962
but I just... I-I haven't
made up my mind yet.

08:24.996 --> 08:26.676
Rachel...
(quiet laugh)

08:26.698 --> 08:28.499
It's really fun to come home
every now and again

08:28.533 --> 08:30.467
and coach a glee club or...

08:30.502 --> 08:32.469
in my case, help your mom
use her grabber tool

08:32.504 --> 08:34.972
to pull a box of cereal
off the top of the fridge,

08:35.006 --> 08:37.508
but you and I both know
that you belong on Broadway.

08:37.542 --> 08:39.309
You need to get your ass
back to New York.

08:39.344 --> 08:41.044
I am going back to New York.
Right after sectionals.

08:41.078 --> 08:42.645
I just don't know yet if
it's gonna be for college

08:42.681 --> 08:43.921
or for Broadway.

08:43.948 --> 08:44.982
(laughs):
What?!

08:45.016 --> 08:46.183
You can't be serious.

08:46.217 --> 08:47.685
Look, my career was on track.

08:47.719 --> 08:49.887
And then I dropped out of NYADA,

08:49.921 --> 08:51.522
and-and my whole
life fell apart.

08:51.556 --> 08:53.490
So now I have the chance
to rectify that mistake

08:53.525 --> 08:56.393
by going back to college, so
what if that's the right choice?

08:56.428 --> 08:58.495
Rachel, your mistake
was not leaving NYADA.

08:58.530 --> 09:00.231
You got the lead role
in <i> Funny Girl.</i>

09:00.265 --> 09:02.032
Nobody could've expected you
to turn that down.

09:02.067 --> 09:04.001
Your mistake was leaving
the show too early

09:04.035 --> 09:05.736
to do that stupid sitcom.

09:05.770 --> 09:09.373
Look, I'm sure that NYADA
is a great place, and maybe

09:09.407 --> 09:10.687
it's because I'm a little biased

09:10.709 --> 09:12.076
because she personally
rejected me,

09:12.110 --> 09:14.545
but unless you want
to be Carmen Tibideaux

09:14.579 --> 09:17.081
and run a school that claims
to be the nation's top

09:17.115 --> 09:19.216
performing arts institution when
they have a known track record

09:19.251 --> 09:21.518
for rejecting really
talented young actors...

09:21.553 --> 09:23.754
(sighs)
you don't need to go to college.

09:23.788 --> 09:25.122
Well, thank you for your input.

09:25.156 --> 09:26.757
I really appreciate
your opinion.

09:26.791 --> 09:28.692
I just...

09:28.727 --> 09:32.129
I have to make
this decision on my own.

09:32.163 --> 09:34.231
Fair enough.

09:34.266 --> 09:36.634
I know that you'll make
the right decision.

09:36.668 --> 09:39.069
I just...

09:41.506 --> 09:44.475
We make really great
music together, Rachel.

09:44.509 --> 09:47.912
We always have.

09:49.247 --> 09:52.349
Think about it.

09:54.119 --> 09:55.719
(school bell rings)

09:55.754 --> 09:57.254
Okay, you're in the back row,
but you're gonna be

09:57.289 --> 09:58.656
the best back-row dancers ever.

09:58.690 --> 09:59.823
Okay? Here we go.

09:59.858 --> 10:02.259
A five, six, seven, eight.

10:02.294 --> 10:04.495
Step together, step together.

10:04.529 --> 10:06.330
Turn. Slide.

10:06.364 --> 10:07.565
Oh, yeah, slide.

10:07.599 --> 10:09.133
WILL and KITTY:
Kick-ball change.

10:09.167 --> 10:10.668
Okay, guys, good,
good, good, good.

10:10.702 --> 10:11.836
Um... we're making progress.

10:11.870 --> 10:13.737
A for effort, all right?

10:13.772 --> 10:15.906
Guys, I'm really sorry.
I'm just, like, not a dancer.

10:15.941 --> 10:17.641
Dude, I'm the one
that's slowing us down.

10:17.676 --> 10:20.110
Okay, anyways,
let's just try it again, okay?

10:20.145 --> 10:22.680
- I'll do it with them. - Okay.
Maybe the music will help.

10:22.714 --> 10:24.081
♪ ♪

10:24.115 --> 10:26.617
Five, six, seven, eight.

10:26.651 --> 10:28.686
Step, step, step, step.

10:28.720 --> 10:30.421
Step together, step together.

10:30.455 --> 10:32.990
Let's just do those turns.

10:33.024 --> 10:35.759
Yes!

